hurricaneforce winds from the desert blasted 
southern california on wednesday collapsing a threestory apartment 
under construction blowing the roofs off homes and knocking over a 
motor home 
weve had reports of power poles blowing over lines down just 
a while ago a man said he had a piece of 2by12 construction lumber 
blow right through his roof said senior deputy gary westmoreland 
spokesman for the san bernardino sheriffs department in the 
foothill community of rancho cucamonga which appeared to be hardest 
hit 
no serious injuries were reported he said 
the santa ana winds which blow out of the desert every fall and 
winter were clocked at 80 mph at the rialto airport said marti 
higgins emergency services coordinator for rancho cucamonga 
in that san bernardino county community the winds collapsed a 
threestory apartment building under construction and blew the roofs 
off at least two homes 
reports of 55 mph winds came from california state university 
northridge and point mugu near ventura the national weather service 
said winds to 40 mph were reported in ontario and to 44 mph in 
blythe near the californianevada border 
small fires were reported throughout the night in rancho 
cucamonga but all were under control ms higgins said 
earlier in the day an apartment under construction in rancho 
cucamonga collapsed in the gale said fire department spokeswoman 
kim agueayo 
they said its a real mess out there and that it was 
windrelated ms agueayo said 
in hollywood on wednesday evening windfanned flames gutted a 
twostory home and leaped to a neighboring residence two dozen 
firefighters battled the blaze said city fire spokesman greg 
acevedo 
in the orange county city of santa ana a tree was blown over 
onto a car 
winds blew between 40 and 50 mph in the mountains and coastal 
areas and gusted up to 60 mph in the canyons the national weather 
service reported 
