<DOCNO> AP881208-0028 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
i think the principal thing that is notable about them as 
described in the speech and then as asked about them during our 
meeting is the attention to trying to affect things like bridging 
capabilities that are offensive in nature and therefore to try to 
have the forces arranged so that theyre more clearly defensive in 
their nature but it still remains that after these reductions take 
place and if nothing else takes place there will be a major 
asymmetry in important categories of force structure for the soviet 
union but nevertheless this is a welcome step in the right 
direction 
q can i just follow that up that was the point that mr 
gorbachev made he said that at the end of these reductions would be 
clear that his forces were in a defensive posture what do you think 
shultz some of the reductions and i mentioned an illustration 
seemed to be pointed in that direction and thats a welcome 
development obviously we have sat i have sat in the hall and 
others watched on television his exposition of this and so im 
giving you a general reaction but obviously were going to sit and 
study this out carefully in the united states and in nato and factor 
it into our thinking about how to position ourselves in the coming 
conventional arms talks 
q mr secretary do you agree with mr gorbachev there are no 
political prisoners in the soviet union and could you tell us what 
you think youre getting two questions here for the price of one 
what do you think of his proposal for a mutual suspension of arms 
supplies to the belligerents in afghanistan 
shultz well as far as prisoners of conscience political 
religious prisoners are concerned there have been a great many 
released a great many in our opinion there still are such 
prisoners in the soviet union but the number is far less in our 
count now there can be differences of opinion about whether 
somebody is in prison because of political expression or religious 
expression or because of violation of the law so what we need and 
what i believe it will be possible to construct is a procedure a 
means through which we will go through with them name by name the 
people on our list and try to determine whether or not that person 
should be released or whether there is some valid reason for the 
imprisonment and i believe that we will be able to get that into 
place and so thatll be a way of answering the question in a kind 
of direct personal sense now youre other question was what 
q the proposal he had a very detailed proposal including the 
mutual suspension of assistance and military supplies to the 
belligerents in afghanistan is that a good idea 
shultz well of course we proposed to the soviet union quite 
some time ago a mutual cessation of supplies and they rejected 
that and so as we insisted and they agreed that there had to be 
symmetry we said well if you insist on supplying then we 
insist that we will have that right actually the mujahedeen 
dont need a lot of more supplies because theyre capturing a great 
deal of supplies 
but at any rate we have been prepared for such a proposal but 
it is tied in with a lot of other things of course the question of 
peacekeeping of trying to help people with reconstruction and 
development that there will be a massive effort needed 
but i dont think there is any way there could be agreement that 
forces would just continue to hold the ground that they have because 
the people of afghanistan broadly speaking do not accept the fact 
that the puppet regime is entitled to hold certain areas of that 
country 
lets review the situation 
there were 15 million people estimated as the population of 
afghanistan in 1979 right now there are a little over three million 
refugees in pakistan a little over two million in iran its 
estimated there are a million and a half casualties over two 
million internal refugees 
so i dont think its surprising that people who have been 
subjected to that kind of turmoil dont want to have anything to do 
with a puppet regime that seemed to have participated in it 
now i think it is a good thing that the soviets are now talking 
directly to the mujahedeen and certainly it is possible the 
mujahedeen are ready to negotiate arrangements whereby there wont 
be attacks on soviet forces as they leave but the key here is 
first and foremost for the soviet troops to leave as they are 
scheduled to do and i believe and hope that that will take place 
q mr secretary you mentioned in your opening statement that 
the presence of vice president bush himself meant a certain 
continuity in the relationship was there any discussion there of 
meetings between mr bush when he becomes president and mr 
gorbachev or of their foreign ministers or any of these other 
