as soon as we get through here i get on my plane and go to brussels 
and ill spend all day tomorrow and friday morning with the nato 
allies and ill spend friday afternoon at the european commission 
and these are the things we talk about and people have different 
views but we kind of put them in a pot and look at them and there 
has emerged from it a rather common view and a cohesive set of 
policies and of course its a constant sort of a moving target in a 
way 
now as far as credit is concerned we have a general 
understanding that noncocom restricted trade with the soviet union 
is no one sees any problem with that and that if there are 
credits they should be on a strictly commercial basis no one feels 
that it is that the soviet union should be subsidized so after 
youve said that then you observe these credits and in terms of 
the total flow of such things at this point at least it doesnt 
appear to me to be any particular problem but the creditors as 
commercial creditors of course have to ask themselves im going 
to loan some money am i going to get it back am i going to get it 
serviced and so on they have to make those calculations as 
people whose money that is 
