<TEXT>
the mousetrap the worlds longestrunning 
play goes on and on and on 
agatha christies thriller has its 15000th performance on 
friday however producer sir peter saunders has become inured to 
such milestones records are meaningless now arent they he 
says 
the play which marked its 36th birthday on nov 25 has 
outlasted nine us presidents and eight british prime ministers to 
become as much a part of london life as big ben 
it originally cost 5000 pounds then about 20000 to stage 
mousetrap when it opened at the ambassadors theater on nov 25 
1952 it since has moved next door to the st martins theater and 
has grossed over 14 million pounds 256 million with its story of 
murderous intrigue on a stormy night at a deserted country manor 
since its premiere 230 actors have appeared in the play 66 
miles of shirts have been ironed and 75 million people have seen 
it consuming 269 tons of ice cream and about 48000 gallons of 
beverages during intermissions 
it started out with richard attenborough playing det sgt 
trotter the famed actorfilmmaker has gone on to become the academy 
awardwinning director of gandhi a chorus line and cry 
freedom 
saunders 77 said he remains mystified by the plays success 
how it got to be the longestrunning play is a question i cant 
answer said saunders who has produced many other christie plays 
all far less durable 
however he acknowledged that the plays momentum is related less 
to the theater than to being a british mainstay 
if you go to paris you have to go see the louvre once even if 
you hate pictures the same applies to the mousetrap he said 
the cast is annually changed to keep the play fresh and its 18th 
director kim grant took over on nov 28 
saunders advises directors against excessive tampering this 
play is like a famous dundee cake which has the same recipe for 100 
years you may change the way its cooked but you dont change the 
ingredients 
grant who directed a 1983 revival of noel cowards hay 
fever has two weeks to rehearse his mousetrap cast as 
opposed to the usual west end londons broadway minimum of four 
he said the material was deceptively difficult 
to make it all plausible and realistic is a great challenge 
he said christies plays are actually very difficult to act 
partly because the dialogue is dated in a way 
the play has been presented in 24 different languages in 44 
countries including a sixmonth offbroadway run in the early 
1950s saunders sold the film rights to romulus films in 1956 with 
the stipulation that no movie version appear until six months after 
the the conclusion of the london run he has twice offered to buy 
back the rights but to no avail 
the producer also has vetoed any broadway runs 
the american press would crucify it he said besides i 
want people to come over here to see it 
</TEXT>
