<TEXT>
atampt and sprint are the winners in a fierce 
contest to provide telephone and hightech communications services 
to the federal government a prize worth up to 25 billion by the 
year 2000 
the losers were martin marietta corp and its bidding partner 
mci 
mci said it may challenge the decision which was made wednesday 
by the general services administration martin marietta asked for a 
detailed briefing on the decision which awarded contracts for a new 
federal telecommunications system called fts2000 providing service 
to government agencies through the 1990s 
gsa awarded the multibilliondollar contracts three years after 
outlining its needs for a new governmentwide phone service system 
that will include video computer and other stateoftheart 
communications 
we are elated us sprint communications co president 
william esrey said 
american telephone amp telegraph co officials expressed equal 
delight at the decision which provided contracts that are among the 
largest ever awarded by the us government aside from military and 
space program purchases 
gsa estimated the combined value of the contracts at between 3 
billion and 10 billion over 10 years but it could reach a maximum 
25 billion the contracts limit government spending to 15 billion 
on the atampt network and 10 billion on sprints 
the estimates are based on the governments purchase of 
longdistance telephone services over a 10year period actual value 
will depend on how much service the government actually uses 
acting gsa administrator richard g austin said atampt received a 
contract to provide approximately 60 percent of the service and 
sprint was awarded the remainder 
mci spokeswoman kathleen keegan said the company would challenge 
the decision in court and before the federal communications 
commission if it determines that atampt used predatory pricing 
that is below its direct costs 
mci priced the longdistance portion of the fts2000 bid as 
aggressively as possible she said if the longdistance portion 
of the winning bids were priced below mcis then we do not believe 
it is possible for the winners to provide that service on a 
profitable basis 
the bidding companies designated subcontractors in their 
proposals to the gsa those included in the losing martin marietta 
bid were gerca americacom and mcdonnell douglas tymnet 
boeing co and computer sciences corp were designated atampt 
subcontractors in the winning bid as well as regional bell 
telephone companies and other local telephone companies 
boeing is to provide program management and information services 
and computer sciences corp will develop and maintain a software 
system for billing the regional telecommunications holding 
companies and local companies will provide local network access 
according to atampt officials 
sprints subcontractor partners include gte and the regional 
telephone companies 
this is an important competitive win for atampt and our partners 
in this project said richard j lombardi atampt vice president for 
federal services 
the system is to be phased in over three years with the first 
users to begin service in 1989 and all federal users to be on line 
in 1991 lombardi said he expected service to be in place by next 
fall 
the contract provides for a new alldigital integrated network 
replacing what is already the worlds largest private 
telecommunications network with service by atampt the current system 
is capable of carrying only voice and slowspeed data transmissions 
the gsa said 
</TEXT>
