<TEXT>
a state supreme court decision allowing much 
of the proposition 103 insurance initiative to take effect but still 
blocking a 20 percent cut in auto insurance rates pending legal 
challenges was hailed by californias attorney general 
the courts action wednesday was the first step toward full 
implementation of proposition 103 said attorney general john van 
de kamp who is defending the measure 
the portions of the consumersponsored measure that the court 
allowed to take effect will force companies to base insurance rates 
primarily on a drivers record and experience and repeal an 
exemption from state antitrust laws for insurance companies among 
other things 
the court continued a stay on enforcing the rate rollback the 
most controversial plank of the initiative and agreed to hear 
insurers claims that the measure would confiscate their property by 
forcing them to operate at a loss 
harvey rosenfield chairman of voter revolt and author of the 
measure said he was disappointed the court did not allow the 
rollback but said he was excited some provisions would take effect 
one insurance industry official expressed disappointment that the 
court modified its stay on the entire initiative but said it was a 
positive sign that the court had blocked the rollback 
at first blush were pleased that the court will hear our 
arguments but we feel the briefing schedule is more relaxed than 
wed like said john kozero a spokesman for firemans fund 
insurance cos no date has been set for a hearing and we hoped 
for a speedy resolution to the case 
the court scheduled written arguments through jan 23 an 
indication that the case is likely to be heard in february a 
decision would be required within the following three months 
the court voted 61 to take the case dissenting justice stanley 
mosk indicated he thought the lawsuits should be dismissed as 
premature a position also taken by sponsors of the initiative 
including consumer advocate ralph nader 
the announcement did not state reasons for the partial lifting of 
the stay or give any other indication of the justices views of the 
lawsuits filed by insurance companies 
the stay was imposed two days after the nov 8 election in which 
proposition 103 was the only one of five insurancerelated 
initiatives to pass 
in wednesdays announcement the court left its stay in place for 
only two of the measures provisions 
one would roll back vehicle and property insurance rates 20 
percent below november 1987 levels and freeze them until november 
1989 unless an insurer could show a substantial threat of 
insolvency the other would take the first steps toward 
establishment of a nonprofit corporation to advocate the insterests 
of insurance consumers 
provisions that will take effect include a ban on cancellation or 
nonrenewal of auto policies except for failure to pay fraud or an 
increase in the risk 
the courts order appeared to support the position of van de kamp 
and private sponsors that a stay of all portions of the measure was 
excessive because most do not threaten the companies with any 
immediate measurable financial harm 
the insurers lawsuits did not attack all provisions of 
proposition 103 but argued that the entire initiative should be 
thrown out if the rate rollback and freeze are declared 
unconstitutional 
</TEXT>
