<TEXT>
china said thursday it welcomed soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachevs decision to cut red army troops by nearly 10 
percent and pull back some troops from the chinese border in 
mongolia 
this is a positive development foreign ministry spokesman li 
zhaoxing told a news conference 
asked if it enhanced prospects for next years proposed 
chinesesoviet summit li said the soviet union indicated it now 
has the intention to clear away all the obstacles standing in the 
way of normalization of chinesesoviet relations we hope the soviet 
union will take further practical steps to eliminate all the 
obstacles once and for all as soon as possible 
gorbachev made the announcement wednesday in a speech to the 
united nations he said the soviet army estimated by western 
experts at 56 million soldiers would be cut by 500000 in the next 
two years and a major portion of soviet troops temporarily 
stationed in mongolia will return home 
troops also will be pulled out of eastern europe he said 
china long has demanded that the soviet union reduce its troop 
presence along their border as a condition for normalizing relations 
after nearly 30 years of estrangement 
the soviet union stations nearly 50000 troops in mongolia which 
has been a close ally since declaring independence from china and 
establishing a socialist government in 1921 the soviets pulled 
about 12000 soldiers out of mongolia in 1987 and china since has 
focused on other issues in its normalization talks with the soviets 
however li said foreign minister qian qichen told soviet 
officials on his visit to moscow last week that china hoped the 
soviets would pull all their troops from mongolia and reduce their 
border forces to a level commensurate with the normal standards of 
good neighborly relations 
li said the soviet side indicated that the process of 
withdrawal of troops from mongolia will be continued 
relations between china and the soviet union long at odds over 
ideological and strategic issues have warmed considerably in the 
past year both sides said during qians visit that the first 
chinesesoviet summit since 1959 could be held next year a specific 
date has not been set 
in addition to a soviet troop reduction along the border chinas 
longstanding conditions for normalizing relations are a soviet 
pullout from afghanistan and vietnams withdrawal from cambodia 
the soviets began withdrawing from afghanistan in may and have 
agreed to work for a settlement of the cambodia issue 
china maintains that vietnam could not continue its decadelong 
occupation of cambodia without soviet aid 
li did not respond directly when asked if a summit could be held 
while vietnamese troops remain in cambodia but said preparations 
for the meeting have already been started 
</TEXT>
