<TEXT>
red cross workers fearful of food riots 
have held off distributing relief supplies to thousands of sudanese 
who lived for months on grass roots and leaves after fleeing civil 
war an official said thursday 
food flown to the area for the past five days is being stored to 
ensure adequate supply when workers begin handing it out said 
pierre pont the khartoum representative of the international 
committee of the red cross 
we couldnt start mass distribution until we had stockpiled 
enough food or else there would be riots said pont who flew 
with wednesdays hercules c130 flight to wau a governmentheld 
southern city surrounded by rebels 
pont said the only food distributed so far has gone to hospital 
patients children in an orphanage and other small vulnerable 
groups 
the rebels in the predominantly animist and christian south are 
fighting a 5yearold war for social reform and autonomy from the 
moslemdominated government in the north relief flights to the 
south began sunday after the rebels dropped their threat to shoot 
down the planes but recent rebel attacks on relief convoys have 
been reported 
beginning sunday the c130 carried 18 tons of food at a time 
from khartoum to wau 625 miles to the southwest and flights from 
kenya took food and medicine to rebelheld towns in the bush pont 
said 
another airlift organized by the united nations is using 
smaller planes to take food to aweil 45 miles northwest of wau 
wau is lacking in everything pont said in an interview it 
is a dramatic situation there but you dont see people dying in the 
streets any more 
before the current airlift he said the last relief shipment 
arrived six or seven months ago in wau whose population swelled to 
100000 from its normal 5000060000 because of people displaced 
over the summer 
they survived by eating roots leaves and grass said pont 
the old people and the children were the worst affected 
but he said all goes well with the airlift we are confident 
that eventually the displaced can be fed and slowly we can improve 
the nutrition status 
