<TEXT>
the united nations honored antiapartheid 
activists nelson and winnie mandela on thursday as it commemorated 
the 40th anniversary of the universal declaration of human rights 
the record of human rights in our age is besmirched by summary 
executions and arbitrary arrests disappearances and torture the 
killing of defenseless demonstrators and detentions for reasons of 
belief or conviction secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar 
told the general assembly 
the universal declaration of human rights adopted without 
dissent by the general assembly dec 10 1948 is the basic un 
document under which members pledge to safeguard life and liberty 
and abolish torture and slavery 
all 159 un member states profess their love for human rights 
but over 80 countries still have prisoners of conscience and torture 
is practiced in more than 60 nations according to franca sciuto 
chairwoman of the executive committee of amnesty international 
ms sciuto and other officials of the londonbased organization 
which won the 1977 nobel peace prize presented perez de cuellar with 
a petition signed by more than 3 million people calling on all 
governments to ratify the worlds human rights treaties to bring 
their own laws and practices into line with them and to act to 
protect human rights worldwide 
only 43 governments for example have signed a protocol allowing 
individuals to petition the united nations with complaints of human 
rights abuses said ms sciuto 
awards were presented to six human rights activists 
mandela leader of the african national congress guerrilla 
organization fighting the south african government has been serving 
a life sentence since 1962 on a conviction of plotting sabotage 
against the state 
winnie mandela his wife since 1958 has become a public symbol 
of resistance to apartheid she has been imprisoned several times 
sometimes in solitary confinement 
the mandelas received their awards in absentia as did murlidar 
devidas amte of india a lawyer and aide to mohandas k gandhi who 
went on to fight for rights for lepers the blind the ill and 
disadvantaged children 
a posthumous award went to leonidas proano of ecuador the roman 
catholic bishop of rio bamba who worked to protect the rights of his 
countrys native people he died in august 
john humphrey of canada received his award in person humphrey 
was director of the un division of human rights from 194666 and 
helped prepare the first draft of the universal declaration of human 
rights he is founding president of canadas section of amnesty 
international 
also present to accept the brass and wood plaque engraved with a 
flame symbolizing human rights was adam lopatka of poland since 
1983 he has chaired the un commission drafting a convention on the 
rights of the child which the world body plans to adopt next year 
he is now first president of polands supreme court 
president franklin d roosevelt and british prime minister 
winston churchill insisted on recognition of human rights in the 
un charter when world war ii discussions laid the groundwork for 
the united nations 
