<TEXT>
light trucks multipurpose vehicles and vans 
would be required to have head restraints like those now used on 
cars under a regulation proposed thursday by the national highway 
traffic safety administration 
head restraints designed to prevent neck injury from whiplash 
during collisions have been required on the front seats of 
passenger cars since 1969 
nhtsa opened a public comment period on the proposal which would 
go into effect sept 1 1991 if adopted the restraints are already 
available for some models of light trucks and vans although they 
are not required by federal regulation 
more and more motorists are using light trucks and vans as 
substitutes for passenger cars said diane steed nhtsa 
administrator studies show head restraints are effective in 
reducing whiplash injuries to frontseat occupants in automobiles 
she said the use of head restraints in light trucks and vans 
could prevent up to 6300 injuries a year 
the restraints are adjustable extensions to the back of the seats 
that keep a passengers head from snapping slightly backward in the 
event of a collision 
nhtsa estimated rearimpact accidents which tend to cause 
whiplash are responsible for 51000 injuries a year to occupants of 
light trucks and vans 
the proposed rule would require the restraints on vehicles with a 
gross weight of 10000 pounds or less 
us manufacturers of light trucks and other vehicles that would 
come under the proposed regulation sold 39 million vehicles this 
year through november up 35 million from the corresponding period 
in 1987 
nhtsa estimated the regulation would on average add 2920 to the 
cost of a vehicle 20 for the head restraint and 920 in extra 
fuel to move the additional seven pounds of weight 
approximately 3 million vehicles would be affected by the 
proposed regulation for a total cost of 876 million per year 
nhtsa said 
general motors corp has installed such restraints on some of its 
models the company said from its washington office 
gm safety liaison dick humphrey was unable to say whether the 
company supported opposed or was neutral on the issue 
we will comment on it to nhtsa and give it our best shot 
he said 
a spokeswoman for ford motor co barbara mansfield said in 
washington the company would have no comment until it had seen the 
proposed rule ford models having captains chairs seats in 
vans which swivel have the head restraints as standard equipment 
</TEXT>
