a threejudge panel of a federal appeals court 
on wednesday upheld a lower court decision to vacate the 1977 
convictions of former gov marvin mandel and five others in a 
political corruption case 
us attorney breckinridge l willcox said he plans to ask the 
us solicitor general for permission to seek a review of the ruling 
by the full 4th circuit court of appeals 
mandel was charged in 1975 with helping irvin kovens w dale 
hess harry w rodgers iii william a rogers and ernest cory sr 
get extra racing days for marlboro race track which they secretly 
owned while he was governor he also was accused of accepting 
350000 in gifts and financial help in a divorce settlement 
in a 21 decision the appeals court panel upheld a nov 12 
1987 decision by us district judge frederic n smalkin that set 
aside the mail fraud convictions of mandel and the others the 
judges agreed with smalkins ruling that the jury at mandels trial 
was allowed to consider a theory of mail fraud law that has since 
been overturned by the us supreme court 
in june 1987 the supreme court ruled that federal mail fraud 
statutes cannot be used to prosecute public officials for defrauding 
citizens of their intangible rights to honest government 
three of the four judges that have recently looked at this case 
have concluded that gov mandel and the other defendants had been 
unjustly convicted for conduct that was not criminal said 
mandels attorney arnold weiner 
willcox contended that the ruling should not be applied to a case 
that was decided 10 years earlier 
mandels conduct then and now is a crime said willcox 
the request for a fullcourt review of the panels ruling will be 
based on a dissenting opinion filed by judge kk hall willcox said 
hall wrote that although their trial included an erroneous jury 
instruction the proceedings were replete with evidence of bribery 
and manipulation their mandel and the others actions were and are 
patently illegal 
mandel was indicted on the mail fraud charges halfway through his 
second fouryear term he remained in office until the day he was 
sentenced and won a reversal on appeal allowing him to resume as 
governor for the last days of his term which expired in 1979 
another appellate review reinstated the conviction and mandel 
served 14 months at a federal prison camp the appellate decision 
stood until smalkins 1987 ruling setting aside the convictions 
