<DOCNO> AP881208-0258 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the second installment in a fivepart christmas 
series on great modern theologians gods 20th century giants 
concerns paul tillich a boundary man with an appeal to 
intellectuals 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
as a young frontline army chaplain in world war i paul tillich 
was so seared by the carnage and bursting shells around him that he 
suffered psychological turmoil for months but he found solace in 
visiting art museums and meditating on great religious paintings 
they have a power to stabilize and power to transform he 
wrote later 
staring at botticellis madonna or other masterworks he 
sensed that divine reality could be revealed through art forms 
expressing the holy through formtranscendence 
that intuition animated the approach of this towering existential 
theologian and philosopher who as he put it labored on the 
boundaries between church and society between faith and culture 
insisting on their interaction 
modern culture has lost its ultimate reference its center of 
meaning its spiritual substance he said leaving a secularized 
void of emptiness anxiety and pointlessness 
a man of natural dignity and gentle warmth tillichs 
unconventional interpretations often shocked the orthodox but they 
radiated an unfettered candor and dominating commitment 
i was thinking about infinity from the age of 8 he said 
he couched religious concepts in fresh often startling 
terminology to prick contemporary minds he called faith ultimate 
concern saying it demands the courage to be in the face of 
threatened nonbeing death he termed christ the new 
being whose incarnation expresses the paradox of god 
accepting a world which rejects him 
tillich called biblical accounts of supernatural occurrences 
symbols but said something happens through them which has 
effects and consequences 
he said christ was the bearer of a new eon who participates 
in human suffering and death overcoming the estrangement between 
man and god through acceptance of the unacceptable 
the saving power of the new being in jesus as the christ he 
said is dependent on mans participation in it 
he said its renewing power often strikes when we are in great 
pain and restlessness or in our indifference our weakness our 
hostility and our lack of direction and composure 
it strikes when we walk through the dark valley of a 
meaningless and empty life at that moment a wave of light 
breaks into our darkness and it is as though a voice were saying 
you are accepted accepted by that which is greater than you 
dont try to analyze or define it he said simply accept the 
fact that you are accepted in that moment grace conquers sin 
and reconciliation bridges the gulf of estrangement and nothing is 
demanded but acceptance to accept oneself as accepted in 
spite of being unacceptable 
tillich as a boundary man standing between a heritage 
imbued with the sacred and an age cut off from it saw himself as a 
mediator working to close a rupture he considered a threat to 
western civilization 
religion is the substance of culture and culture the form of 
religion he said there is no life where there is no 
otherness 
he died in 1965 at age 79 scorned by traditionalists but 
enduringly esteemed by others for his powerful reformulation of 
christian concepts 
he tackled the centurys most salient tension between 
religion and secularization wrote mark kline taylor a princeton 
theologian in a l987 book paul tillich 
he exerted a formative influence pointing theologians toward 
renewed christian hope along a journey where risks of the void 
attend each step they take taylor wrote 
using his inventive often arresting religious lexicon tillich 
said god was not a being or even the highest being alongside 
other beings 
when applied to god superlatives become diminuitives he 
said he termed god beingitself or ground of being the 
dynamic power of being in everything and above everything that 
energizes and gives cohesion to all authentic endeavor 
however he says people have become estranged from the ultimate 
power of being submerged in anxiety loneliness and guilt 
disillusioned by always collapsing idolatries of nationalism 
technology possessions sex or success 
he described sin as separation separation from others from 
ones self and from the ground of ones being 
we not only suffer because of the selfdestructive 
consequences of our separation but also know why we suffer 
tillich said we know that we are estranged from something to 
which we really belong 
we feel that something radical total and unconditional is 
demanded of us but we rebel against it try to escape its urgency 
and will not accept its promise 
this awareness of our separation from the rest of life is most 
acute when we are surrounded by it in noises and talk he said 
such as the intense loneliness that can descend in a crowded room 
we realize then much more than in moments of solitude how 
strange we are to each other how estranged life is from life he 
said 
yet we cannot escape the ground of our being but are 
bound to it for all eternity just as we are bound to ourselves and 
to all other life we always remain in the power of that from which 
we are estranged 
that fact brings us to the ultimate depth of sin separated and 
yet bound estranged and yet belonging destroyed and yet preserved 
that state which is called despair the sickness unto death 
tillich reared in germany as the son of a lutheran minister and 
ordained himself initially taught at german universities but his 
early criticisms of hitler led to his expulsion in 1933 along with 
many jewish professors including the great martin buber 
tillich once observed he was the first nonjewish academician 
to be so honored emigrating to the united states he became a 
citizen and taught for 32 years at new yorks union theological 
seminary harvard and the university of chicago 
in his gravelly accented voice he engaged students in searching 
dialogues relishing afterhours bull sessions 
his threevolume systematic theology and numerous other books 
interweave disciplines of history psychology political science 
art and philosophy he gained a wide audience among government and 
academic leaders believers and nonbelievers 
f forrester church a unitarian universalist minister terms 
tillich an apostle to the intellectuals adding in a 1987 
anthology the essential tillich 
we need a tillich to guide us through the perils of our age 
tillich said it was blasphemous and ridiculous to try to 
prove existence of an infinite god utterly beyond finite human 
categories 
yet he said humans realize their limited finitude and by that 
very fact transcend it in awareness of some potential infinity 
he says that realization is an existential pointer to god god 
is the answer to the question implied in mans finitude he said 
yet anxiety and doubt remain divine reality would not be that 
at all if people could verify it he said without conquered 
doubt there is no faith faith must overcome something it must 
leap over the ordinary processes 
faith is the courage that conquers doubt not by removing it 
but by taking it as an element into itself 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

