<DOCNO> AP881208-0259 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
out of friendship for one of the leaders martin buber was 
marching in a street procession as the marchers passed a cafe he 
locked gazes with a musician hed dined with the day before 
the musician apparently saw me alone and waved to me buber 
recounted straightway it seemed to me as though i were taken out 
of the procession and the presence of my marching friends and set 
there confronting the musician 
i forgot that i was walking along with the same step i felt 
that i was standing over there by the man who had called out to me 
and without a word with a smile of understanding was answering 
him 
by the time buber again became conscious of the procession around 
him the cafe was far behind 
the incident that minor transporting moment with the musician 
reflects the pervasive thesis of a man regarded as one of the 20th 
centurys greatest philosophers 
buber maintained that human wholeness its vitalizing reality 
exists only in between separate persons other creatures nature 
and god a connecting mutuality recognized only in genuine 
encounter 
all real living is meeting he said real living exists only 
in honest open giveandtake between separate selves an interflow 
that surpasses both and augments each 
through unaffected personal engagement in the encounter 
participants are lifted out of themselves he said the extended 
lines of relations meet in the eternal thou the center in 
the consummate reality of god 
in every genuinely open contact we are stirred by the breath 
of a thou that is of eternal life he said if you hallow this 
life you meet the living god 
bubers ideas spawned a widespread relational theology 
throughout christianity and also in judaism sometimes in simplified 
popular versions 
buber a jew whose christian wife converted to judaism was an 
influential figure in the expanding concourse between these linked 
traditions 
in his book about christianjewish ties two types of faith 
buber said from my youth onwards i have found in jesus my great 
brother 
that christianity has regarded and does regard him as god and 
savior has always appeared to me a fact of the highest importance 
which for his sake and my own i must endeavor to understand 
my own fraternally open relationship to him has grown ever 
stronger and clearer 
a short stocky man with a flowing white beard and disarming 
smile buber was born in austria and taught at universities in 
germany until silenced by the nazis in 1934 
emigrating to israel he taught at the hebrew university in 
jerusalem lectured widely and wrote many books including a german 
translation of the bible and his bestselling i and thou 
an hasidic scholar and independentminded zionist he advocated 
arabjewish cooperation and was criticized by some fellow jews for 
it his death in 1965 at age 87 prompted an unprecedented tribute a 
delegation of arab students placed a wreath on his grave 
for his relational theology buber coined an almost poetic 
terminology to distinguish between iit relations which reduce 
people and things to utilitarian objects and ithou relations 
which enhance and authenticate the being of both partners 
buber saw modern humanity as trapped in a selfinsulating i 
of individualism that hardens into the world of it 
in an atmosphere of depersonalizing forces and mechanized 
systems people adjust themselves to the apparatus as if mere 
cogs in it he said debasing mans power to enter into relation 
the sickness of our age is like that of no other age under 
the tyranny of the exuberantly growing it he said the 
quasibiological and quasihistorical thoughts of today have 
worked together to establish a more tenacious and oppressive 
fatalism than has ever before existed 
this is the exalted melancholy of our age that every thou in 
our world must become an it he said 
yet at times a person shuddering at the alienation between the 
i and the world comes to reflect that something is to be done 
buber said 
as when in the grave nighthour you lie racked by waking dream 
bulwarks have fallen away and the abyss is screaming and note 
amid your torment there is life if i could only get through to 
it 
buber sees earthly existence as a duality in which people 
necessarily objectify their surroundings as its so as to make 
for orderly arrangements bounded measured and codified 
this structuring is needed for functioning of institutions 
sciences and societies and is not itself evil but can be degrading 
if it is the predominating attitude he said adding 
without it man cannot live but he who lives with it alone is 
not a man 
to truly live requires a continual turning to relations he 
said a repeated crossing the threshold between a functional 
environment of things binding people most of the time and the holy 
place of dialogue connections and mutuality 
he said mere greetings can reflect the different dispositions 
such as the virtually impersonal hello how are you and the 
direct bodyrelated greeting of african kaffirs i see you 
the fuller reality the revealing by two people of the thou to 
one another can be seen especially in good marriages he said 
he who lives with a woman and brings her life to present 
realization in his is able to look in the thou of her eyes into a 
beam of the eternal thou he said 
buber says this enlarging connecting quality can be realized not 
only between persons but with all nature for example a cat or 
tree can be viewed merely as of a certain type dimension 
conformation and color but none of these is the whole being of 
the cat or tree he said 
if alert to the simple magic of life in nature there is a 
reciprocity of the being itself he said you say thou to the 
tree and give yourself to it and it says thou to you and gives 
itself to you something lights up and approaches us from the 
source of being 
buber attributes this innate reality of all created being to the 
primal the origin and says it shows up in primitive peoples 
intercourse with nature and in a young childs personification of 
toys animals and objects 
it is the instinct to make everything into thou to give 
relation to the universe he said 
an overshadowing peril to humanity is to sink into selfabsorbed 
individualism sundered from connected being buber said 
individualism neither shares in nor obtains any reality the 
more a man humanity is mastered by individuality the deeper does 
the i sink into the unreality of a hidden subterranean 
canceled existence 
he said people need to confirm one another in their 
individual being by means of genuine meeting it is from one man 
to another that the heavenly bread is passed 
</TEXT>
