<TEXT>
this fourth story of a fivepart christmas series 
on great modern theologians gods 20th century giants is about 
karl rahner and rudolf bultmann 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a reader once sent renowned roman catholic scholar karl rahner a 
cartoon depicting him as a brainy theological atomic physicist 
expounding from a desk high above others 
below him busy multipliers carve up his ideas handing the 
pieces down to popularizing simplifiers off to the side a 
puzzled jesus says i dont understand 
smiling about the cartoon in a 1979 interview rahner said it 
captures to a large extent the lot of theologians in modern 
times because their work is often regarded as unintelligible 
nonsense 
one should not get up on his high horse and decide that 
specific questions have been settled for another or for oneself 
he said especially today in our skeptical and relativistic age 
a modest unpretentious streak marked this 20th century 
theological giant who scaled the intellectual heights of faith and 
with a common touch rendered them in terms of ordinary life 
he said our limited humanity cant imagine the unconditional 
immeasurable god but he is already present in human existence 
silent and hidden it is a knowledge we cannot grasp but 
whereby we are grasped 
rahner is often called an incarnationalist or 
anthropocentrist who saw divine promptings in the human grain 
he wanted to focus more keenly on this internal presence rather 
than try to to drum into somebody an authoritative doctrine that 
is external 
rahner worked to bridge the gap between theological complexities 
and contemporary thought 
he also wrote gently of the gracebestowing significance of 
everyday living such as working playing laughing sleeping 
life bears a supernatural element that can be suppressed and also 
can be realized and experienced existentially from within he 
said to him that simple intimate indefinable mysticism of 
everyday life is the essence of christianity 
rahner called christ the revealing selfcommunication of 
god the mystery of god sharing himself with us 
this is a quiet unobtrusive process at work daily he said 
yet it is the great sign that god himself has directly intervened 
in the world 
rahner originated a new religious category anonymous 
christianity saying it embraced buddhists various other 
nonchristians and even athiests who are conscientious upright and 
caring 
some kind of faith in god is basically there whether they know 
it or not he said they are a part of a christianity that does 
not call itself christianity pagans who have received grace 
but who are not aware of it 
rahner tangled often with vatican authorities who at times 
castigated and even silenced him but they never shifted him from 
his humanizing tack 
ecclesiastical dignitaries tend to embrace elaborate dogmas 
on which modern man is quite incapable of basing his faith he 
commented 
despite his conflicts with officialdom rahner emerged as an 
influential adviser at the reforming second vatican council of 
196265 
his last book unity of the churches an actual possibility 
which he wrote with fellow german catholic theologian heinrich 
fries jolted churchdom it declared that all main branches of 
christianity protestant eastern orthodox and roman catholic 
sufficiently agreed on basic concepts to unite in one church 
this unity is a matter of life or death for christiandom at a 
time when faith in god and christ are most seriously threatened 
wrote rahner and fries 
they proposed that traditions of each denomination be continued 
within a unified church recognizing the popes leadership but 
without binding authority making churchwide decisions in inclusive 
councils and sharing pulpits and holy communion 
rahner a jesuit priest was a friend of another theological 
titan rudolf bultmann a fellow german lutheran and 
groundbreaking thinker who modified the contours of contemporary 
theology 
he like rahner sought to link theology and modern thought but 
in a more radical way 
theology will never be the same because of bultmann never 
ever said american methodist scholar shubert m ogden 
bultmann the most controversial of the centurys theological 
stars was attacked in many countries as a heretic for his 
demythologizing of the bible 
the bibles prescientific view of a universe with heaven above 
hell below and earth between traversed by angels and demons was 
incredible to modern man he maintained he said it should be 
replaced with an updated worldview that preserved the profound 
meanings inside the obsolete framework 
he said stripping away the antiquated trappings of the new 
testament would clarify the basic message so it could be heard that 
message he said is the power of gods word which encounters man 
in the proclamation of jesus christ 
christ is god breaking in bultmann said 
he regarded jesus as a historical figure and his crucifixion as 
factual much however about the life of jesus his miracles the 
resurrection and his ascent into heaven were myths the early 
christians used to explain how jesus reconciled humanity to god 
bultmann said 
to bultmann myths were not fairy tales but covers for deep 
realities the resurrection he said shows death is not a sinking 
into nothing but that the same god who is always coming to us 
also meets us in our death 
bultmann 91 when he died in 1976 remained a powerful influence 
on protestant and catholic biblical studies although his views were 
spurned by literalists his existential approach somewhat resembled 
that of rahner who nevertheless adhered more thoroughly to 
classical interpretations 
rahner died in 1984 at the age of 80 
we are living in the midst of a transitional period of great 
scope and depth that threatens faith but holds eventual promise 
for it rahner said humanity he said is fashioning an utterly new 
environnment in which technology replaces nature itself 
while nature once seemed mysterious we no longer live in 
nature we transform it he said in wide areas we do not face a 
nature that god has made but one that we have made 
like nature the manstructured environment remains finally 
uncontrollable and more dangerous its future shrouded in 
mist he said instead of mystery arising from nature it now is 
welling up out of man himself 
while religious elements in man temporarily have been 
pushed into the background rahner said man has only to make 
himself at home again in his new environment as he once was in 
nature and his religious awareness will arise again to a degree 
and extent hardly imaginable today 
as in such an atmosphere bultmann noted that often when first 
listening to a symphony the basic melody eludes the listener 
because you are deafened by the fullness of detail and a 
veritable sea of sounds and impressions 
but in a while he said as with one magicial stroke a single 
unified world emerges from the confused welter of sound and it 
becomes clear that the fundamental tone was there all the time 
so it is in discerning the mighty note of god in the 
temporary confusion bultmann said it is always the same old 
theme endlessly proceeding in ever new ways always more 
tempestuous always more powerful 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

