<DOCNO> AP881208-0261 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the final installment of a fivepart christmas 
series on great modern theologians gods 20th century giants 
concerns reinhold niebuhr and dietrich bonhoeffer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
before a roomful of notables gathered to honor him an elderly 
reinhold niebuhr ticked off various trends that he saw as making a 
mess of the world he paused grinned and said but i like it 
he relished the struggles for good in this clamorous world and 
for a halfcentury stayed wholeheartedly in their midst striving 
for sense and reason 
he that sitteth in the heavens shall laugh he frequently 
said quoting a psalm about gods laughter at humanitys blustering 
presumptions of absolute solutions 
the whole drama of human history is under the scrutiny of a 
divine judge who laughs at human pretensions without being hostile 
to human aspirations he said 
upholding what he termed christian realism niebuhr is 
generally regarded as the centurys premier american theologian 
no one else could speak with such authority to christian jew 
and nonbeliever wrote historian richard fox in a 1987 biography 
he was assuredly an american phenomenon 
often quoted by presidents and statesmen he was both incisive 
thinker and working dynamo a media commentator social critic 
political organizer prolific author and seminary professor 
at new yorks union theological seminary he customarily reserved 
thursday nights for at home conversations with students nimbly 
dissecting their questions striding the room and trailing cigarette 
smoke 
niebuhr sought to establish relevance and working 
applicability of faith to the world he disdained sanctimony and 
cant in both religion and politics 
after accusing president richard nixon of court piety in the 
white house and madness in expanding the vietnam war niebuhr 
said god told us to love our enemies not to like them 
while niebuhr said inherent sin was the one church doctrine 
thoroughly verified by history he also insisted doggedly on the 
undetermined possibilities of the good and the obligations to 
realize them in this world always recognizing there will be 
some corruption as well as deficiency of virtue and truth in 
every achievement 
he saw christ as the final perfection of man impossible 
possiblity citadel of hope and moral beauty the 
redemptive force 
christ is the symbol of ultimate reality who reveals that 
selfsacrificial love though crushed by history rises above it 
niebuhr said 
humanitys existence is never fulfilled he said this is the 
final enigma for which there is no answer except by faith and 
hope 
this was the prodding christian realism that niebuhr injected 
into the political sphere he himself abandoned early socialism and 
pacifism as unreal idealisms and saw prospects in this world as 
always fragmentary a matter of compromises and tradeoffs for 
partial relative good 
often he said there are no clearcut right decisions only 
ambiguous alternatives and the hope that good outweighs evil for 
instance nuclear deterrence leaves both superpowers clinging to 
nuclear weapons for security yet standing in terror of them 
a sorry predicament he said but imposed by circumstances 
he saw reality as shot through with irony ambiguity contradiction 
and paradox 
the biblical interpretation of the human situation is ironic 
rather than tragic or pathetic he said since people are free to 
do good but in their predatory selfinterest do not 
niebuhr helped pull americans from early isolationist attitudes 
toward hitler and urged opening us shores to european jews he was 
among the first christian theologians to oppose attempts to convert 
jews 
in the prelude to world war ii he brought to union theological 
seminary a brilliant young lutheran scholar dietrich bonhoeffer 
whom he had met in europe 
in 1930s germany bonhoeffer had been a marked man to gestapo 
eyes having early assailed hitlers antijewish doctrines 
brought to america for safety in 1939 he remained only a short 
time telling niebuhr he had to share the trials of this time with 
my people he returned worked with the resistance ran an 
underground seminary and joined the abortive plot by german officers 
to assassinate hitler 
confined in a series of concentration camps he was hanged april 
9 1945 at age 39 shortly before the camp was liberated by 
american troops 
a christian realist of niebuhrs stripe bonhoeffers widely 
read writings such as the cost of discipleship and letters 
and papers from prison have made him another of the centurys 
theological giants 
like niebuhr he said christians should not withdraw into 
otherworldliness but plunge into the secular world struggling and 
suffering as christ did to work some good 
he said this world come of age with all its technical 
advances seems to round itself off without god feeling 
increasingly able to deal with its questions without recourse to 
conventional religion 
he called for a religionless christianity stripped of its 
concentration on private piety and otherworldliness and lived in 
deeds of service to participate in the suffering of god in 
christ 
it should not be faith that flees the world but the one that 
endures the world he said 
he said god was not on the borders of life but at its center 
we should find god in what we do know not in what we dont 
those who evade the earth do not find god they find a world 
beyond to be sure but one that is not gods world that world 
which is dawning in this world 
in a similar vein niebuhr said 
the new world must be built by resolute men who when hope is 
dead will hope by faith who will neither seek premature escape from 
the guilt of history nor yet call the evil which taints all their 
achievements good 
concerning latterday forms of escapism niebuhr said 
insecurities of our age strongly tempt this generation not to 
utopianism of yesterday but to flight into any kind of storm cellar 
of religious security tied to otherworldliness irresponsible to 
the present world 
he denounced americas consumer culture and 
moralsounding political deceptions its religious smugness 
and easy answers 
he assailed the 1963 supreme court decision outlawing school 
prayer saying it suppressed free exercise of religion and 
imposed a secular philosophy that is itself a religion 
he saw will to power as the essence of politics restrained 
only by the checksandbalances of the us constitution 
mans capacity for justice makes democracy possible he said 
but mans inclination to injustice makes democracy necessary 
beginning as a lutheranreformed pastor in detroit where his 
prolabor tangles with the auto industry drew national attention he 
shifted to union seminary his base for 32 years after retirement 
he served on various study commissions and still poured out a 
torrent of books and articles he died in 1971 shortly at 78 
the human story is too grand and too awful to be told without 
reverence for the mystery and the majesty that transcends all human 
knowledge he said 
only humble men who recognize the mystery and the majesty are 
able to face both the beauty and terror of life without exulting 
over its beauty or becoming crushed by its terror 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

