we consider it to be very important said bagrat aroutiounov 
the soviet director of overseas exhibitions he said the event is 
the first pure commercial trade show ever mounted by the soviet 
union in this country 
previous trade shows had primarily political aims aroutiounov 
said and were intended to show off the advantages of a 
statecontrolled economy this years show has a single thoroughly 
capitalist goal profit 
furthermore aroutiounov said this will be the first time that a 
soviet trade fair has been financed by the participants 
cooperatives foreign trade organizations and enterprises and not 
the government 
the show officially titled the soviet export goods exhibition 
initially was scheduled to begin dec 14 but was hastily 
rescheduled to dec 8 to coincide with gorbachevs visit to new york 
fortyeight participants will display approximately 4500 
products including tractors toys computer programs jewelry 
cars bicycles vodka and hunting rifles the soviet house of 
fashion design will present fabulous russian furs as well as 
jackets and suits inspired by the soviet military uniform 
in addition some us companies have rented booths to show off 
the benefits of their business ties with the soviet union the 
soviets are looking not only for buyers wolstenholme said but for 
american companies willing to take part in joint business ventures 
i think mr gorbachev himself said that the only limit is the 
creativity of the american businessman he said 
but other observers see tougher barriers to improvements in 
ussoviet trade one limit is the soviet shortage of hard currency 
since the ruble cannot be converted into western currencies the 
soviets must pay for american goods and services with gold or 
western currency given the soviets trade imbalance with the west 
the policy has builtin limitations 
some have speculated that soviet economists would propose plans 
at the fair for making the ruble convertible aroutiounov said he 
expected the process would take two or three years maybe longer 
but us officials scoff at such suggestions you probably 
believe in santa claus too zabijaka said in reference to the 
soviet proposals 
according to commerce department figures the soviet union 
exported 500 million worth of products to the united states last 
year and imported 15 billion worth of american goods including 
900 million worth of grain 
that represents a sharp drop from the peak year of 
sovietamerican trade 1979 when the soviets imported 36 billion 
in us goods and exported 900 million to the us 
those levels dropped sharply when the us imposed a limited 
grain embargo in the wake of the soviet invasion of afghanistan and 
sharply reduced purchases of soviet goods 
