<TEXT>
the us dollar remained weaker against the japanese 
yen friday following finance minister kiichi miyazawas resignation 
while share prices rebounded slightly on the tokyo stock exchange 
the dollar which opened at 12220 yen was changing hands at 
12233 yen at midday down 069 yen from thursdays close of 12302 
yen it moved in a range of 12210 yen to 12245 yen 
the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues a 29192point 
loser thursday edged up 1076 points or 004 percent to finish 
the morning session at 2976966 
the dollar began trading sharply lower in tokyo following an 
overnight plunge in new york where it closed at 12228 yen down 
140 yen 
the dollars fall in new york was attributed to dealers 
disappointment about a still unclear us reaction to soviet leader 
mikhail gorbachevs pledge at the united nations to unilaterally 
reduce soviet troops and cut the number of soviet conventional 
weapons 
in tokyo anticipation of miyazawas resignation friday left many 
currency dealers waiting on the sidelines said mitsuhiko kinugasa 
of daiwa bank 
many traders speculate that the resignation of miyazawa who 
has opposed a weaker dollar would damage current international 
monetary coordination said kinugasa that gave the market 
strong bearish sentiments toward the dollar today 
miyazawa who had hinted at his resignation earlier formally 
announced he was stepping down to help clear opposition to tax 
reform legislation under discussion in parliament 
the announcement of miyazawas resignation came just as the stock 
market ended its morning session 
share prices rose slightly but were mixed many investors were 
inclined to sit on the sidelines following thursdays sharp fall 
said a dealer with a major securities firm speaking on condition of 
anonymity 
